For metric-based methods,
TableÂ 1 shows results for
ProtoNet on FC100.
The simple GMM method significantly outperforms the other active learning strategies on all problem variants considered here.
As previously reported (Hacohen etÂ al., 2022; Yehuda etÂ al., 2022),
uncertainty-based methods are significantly worse than random selection in this low-budget regime.

For optimization-based, TableÂ 2 shows results with MAML on MiniImageNet.
Similar to TableÂ 1, GMM again significantly outperforms the other strategies in most cases.
The performance of ProbCover is sometimes much lower than other methods due to its radius parameter, which is very difficult to tune, with the best choice changing dramatically depending on the sub-task even though Yehuda etÂ al. (2022) proposed to fix this parameter per dataset (see AppendixÂ F for more).
Results for ANIL on TieredImageNet and MetaOptNet on FC100 are provided in AppendixÂ G.

ProbCover and Typiclust use self-supervised features to actively select new data points to annotate, since there are not enough labeled data to train a classifier to output meaningful features.
Instead, they utilize the features from SimCLRÂ (Chen etÂ al., 2020).
To validate if it is better to use the features from a meta learner than SimCLR in meta-learning, we compare SimCLR features to the features from either MAML or ProtoNet for Typiclust and ProbCover as shown in TableÂ 12 and TableÂ 13.
Here, we use MiniImageNet and FC100 datasets for MAML and ProtoNet, respecitvely as with TableÂ 2 and TableÂ 1.
For both Typiclust and ProbCover, although there are a couple of cases where SimCLR features are better, it is significantly worse than MAML and ProtoNet features in general.
It intuitively makes sense because 1) meta learners are trained with large enough data points and 2) it is likely that the information in self-supervised features do not align with that in meta learners.

A9.T12.caption: Table 12: Comparison of MAML and SimCLR features for Typiclust in meta-test time.
references:
ProbCover and Typiclust use self-supervised features to actively select new data points to annotate, since there are not enough labeled data to train a classifier to output meaningful features.
Instead, they utilize the features from SimCLRÂ (Chen etÂ al., 2020).
To validate if it is better to use the features from a meta learner than SimCLR in meta-learning, we compare SimCLR features to the features from either MAML or ProtoNet for Typiclust and ProbCover as shown in TableÂ 12 and TableÂ 13.
Here, we use MiniImageNet and FC100 datasets for MAML and ProtoNet, respecitvely as with TableÂ 2 and TableÂ 1.
For both Typiclust and ProbCover, although there are a couple of cases where SimCLR features are better, it is significantly worse than MAML and ProtoNet features in general.
It intuitively makes sense because 1) meta learners are trained with large enough data points and 2) it is likely that the information in self-supervised features do not align with that in meta learners.
